1- Why each element was added

Second HAProxy (load balancer cluster) — the original design had a single HAProxy which was itself a SPOF: if it went down, the entire site became unreachable even though the backend servers were healthy. Adding a second HAProxy and configuring both as a cluster (using keepalived + VRRP) solves this. Both nodes share a virtual IP and exchange heartbeats. If the active node fails, the passive one claims the virtual IP and takes over in seconds — with no manual intervention. This is what "configured as a cluster with the other one" means.
Dedicated web server (Nginx only) — previously Nginx shared a server with the application server and MySQL, competing for the same CPU and RAM. A dedicated web server means Nginx can use all available resources for what it does best: handling HTTP connections, serving static assets, applying caching headers, and doing SSL/TLS work. It can also be scaled independently if static file traffic grows.
Dedicated application server — the application server now gets full access to its machine's CPU and memory for running business logic. This matters because app servers tend to be CPU-intensive and bursty. Dedicating a server also makes horizontal scaling straightforward: if load increases, you add more app server nodes behind the load balancer without touching the web or database tiers.
Dedicated database server — MySQL benefits enormously from dedicated hardware. Its InnoDB buffer pool can be configured to consume most of the server's RAM (for in-memory caching of hot data). The disks can be fast NVMe SSDs tuned for I/O-heavy workloads. With a shared server, a spike in app-server CPU would steal resources from the DB, causing query latency to spike. Isolation eliminates this.

2- Web server vs application server — the distinction

A web server (Nginx) speaks HTTP. Its job is to accept TCP connections, parse HTTP headers, serve files from disk, and route requests. It doesn't understand your application's business logic.
An application server runs your code. It takes a request (from Nginx), executes logic (authentication, database queries, computation), and returns a structured response. Examples: Gunicorn (Python), Puma (Ruby), Node.js process, PHP-FPM.
Splitting them means each can be optimized, scaled, and restarted independently — a code deploy that restarts the app server doesn't affect Nginx's ability to serve cached static files.
